The box is simply a container with a shadow, a border, a radius, and some padding.

      = box []
        [ p [] 
          [ text "I'm the box ghost!" ]
        ]
values.type: Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Elements.Box msg

values.name: content
values.comment:
A single class to handle WYSIWYG-generated content, where only HTML tags are available.

    import Bulma.Modifiers exposing (Size(Normal))

    myContent : Html msg
    myContent
      = content Normal []
        [ p [] [ text "Lorem ipsum..." ] 
        ]
        
It can handle almost any HTML element, including:
- `p`
- `ul` / `ol` / `dl`
- `h1` through `h6`
- `blockquote`
- `em` & `strong`
- `table`, `tr`, `th`, and `td` tables
values.type: Bulma.Modifiers.Size -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Elements.Content msg

values.name: buttonModifiers
values.comment:
The basic defaults for buttons.

    import Bulma.Modifiers exposing ( State(Blur) 
                                    , Color(Default)
                                    , Size(Normal)
                                    )
                                   
    myButtonModifiers : ButtonModifiers msg
    myButtonModifiers 
      = { disabled = False
        , outlined = False
        , inverted = False
        , size     = Normal
        , state    = Blur
        , color    = Default
        }

values.name: connectedFieldGroup
values.comment:
This is a container for gluing controls together on the same line. 
This variation will connect them as "addons".

    myFieldGroup : Html msg
    myFieldGroup
      = fieldGroup Centered []
        [ controlInput myControlInputModifiers [] [] [] 
        , control myControlModifiers []
          [ button myButtonModifiers [] []
          ]
        ]
values.type: Bulma.Modifiers.HorizontalAlignment -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Form.Control msg) -> Bulma.Form.Field msg

values.name: control
values.comment:
Controls are containers for singlular form controls.
They can only contain the folling elements:
- `label` (for radio and checkbox)
- `input`
- `select`
- `button`
- `icon`

You really shouldn't need to use this function.
`controlLabel`, `controlButton`, `controlInput`, etc. should be everything you need.
values.type: Bulma.Form.ControlModifiers msg -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Form.Control msg

values.name: controlButton
values.comment:
type Msg = DoSomething
    
    myButton : Html Msg
    myButton
      = let myControlAttrs : List (Attribute Msg)
            myControlAttrs = []
            myButtonAttrs   : List (Attribute Msg)
            myButtonAttrs   = [ onClick DoSomething ]

        in  controlButton myButtonModifiers 
            myControlAttrs
            myButtonAttrs
            [ text "Click me!"
            ]
values.type: Bulma.Form.ButtonModifiers msg -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Form.Control msg

values.name: controlCheckBox
values.comment:
type Msg = UpdateChoice Bool
    
    myCheckBox : Html Msg
    myCheckBox
      = let myControlAttrs  : List (Attribute Msg)
            myControlAttrs  = []
            myLabelAttrs    : List (Attribute Msg)
            myLabelAttrs    = []
            myCheckBoxAttrs : List (Attribute Msg)
            myCheckBoxAttrs = [ onCheck UpdateChoice ]

        in  controlCheckBox
            myControlAttrs
            myLabelAttrs
            myCheckBoxAttrs
            [ text "I don't agree to the terms and conditions"
            ]

type Msg = UpdateChoice String

      = let myControlAttrs : List (Attribute Msg)

            myLabelAttrs   : List (Attribute Msg)
            myLabelAttrs   = []
            myRadioAttrs   : List (Attribute Msg)

        in  controlRadio myControlAttrs
            [ controlRadioButton "answer"
              myLabelAttrs
              (value "1" :: myRadioAttrs)

            , controlRadioButton "answer"
              myLabelAttrs

values.name: controlSelect
values.comment:
type Msg = UpdateChoice String
    
    myOption : (String,String) -> Html msg
    myOption (key,val)
      = option [ value val ]
        [ text key
        ]

    mySelect : Html Msg
    mySelect
      = let myControlAttrs  : List (Attribute Msg)
            myControlAttrs  = []
            mySelectAttrs : List (Attribute Msg)
            mySelectAttrs = [ onInput UpdateChoice ]

        in  controlSelect myControlModifiers 
            myControlAttrs
            mySelectAttrs
        <|  List.map myOption
        <|  [ (   "grow", "eat me"   )
            , ( "shrink", "drink me" )
            ]

values.name: field
values.comment:
Fields are containers for Controls.
Usually this will be a single `control`, with optional an `label` and `help`.

    import Bulma.Form exposing ( field
                               , label
                               , controlInput
                               , controlModifiers
                               , help
                               )

    myField : Html msg
    myField
      = field []
        [ controlLabel [] []
        , controlInput myControlInputModifiers [] [] [] 
        , controlHelp myControlModifiers [] []
        ]

        [ controlInput myControlInputModifiers [] [] [] 
        , control myControlModifiers []
          [ button myButtonModifiers [] []
          ]

values.name: multilineFieldGroup
values.comment:
This is a container for gluing controls together when you expect it to take up multiple lines.

    myControlButton : String -> Html msg
    myControlButton buttonText
      = control myControlModifiers []
        [ button myButtonModifiers []
          [ text buttonText ]
        ]

    myFieldGroup : Html msg
    myFieldGroup
      = multilineFieldGroup []
     <| List.map myControlButton
     <| List.map toString
     <| List.range 0 10

values.comment:
A simple container to center your content horizontally.

    myContainer : Html msg
    myContainer
      = container []
        [ p []
          [ text "My container is centered on a desktop!"
          ]
        ]

Containers can be used in any context, but mostly as a direct child of:
- `navbar`
- `hero`
- `section`
- `footer`

values.name: column
values.comment:
A column element that is meant to be placed in `columns`.

    myColumn : Html msg
    myColumn
      = column myColumnModifiers []
        [ h1 [] [ text "Lorem" ]
        , h2 [] [ text "ipsum" ]
        , h3 [] [ text "dolor" ]
        , h4 [] [ text "sit" ]
        , h5 [] [ text "amet" ]
        ]
values.type: Bulma.Grid.ColumnModifiers -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Grid.Column msg

values.name: columnModifiers
values.comment:
Default offsets and widths for individiual columns. 
Everything defaults to `Auto`.

values.name: columns
values.comment: Make a columnar grid! The widths of all your columns should be no greater than twelve.
values.type: Bulma.Grid.ColumnsModifiers -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Grid.Column msg) -> Html.Html msg

values.name: columnsModifiers
values.comment:
Default column attributes.

    myColumnsModifiers : ColumnsModifiers
    myColumnsModifiers 
      = { multiline          = False
        , gapless            = False             
        , display            = TabletAndBeyond
        , verticallyCentered = False
        }
    
    myColumnsModifiers == columnsModifiers

values.name: narrowColumn
values.comment:
Narrow columns are used just like other columns, but they only take up as much space as they need.

The other non-narrow columns will take up the remaining space.

    myNarrowColumn : Html msg
    myNarrowColumn
      = let offset : Width
            offset = Auto
        in narrowColumn offset []
           [ text "I only take what I need!"
           ]
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Grid.Column msg

values.name: tile
values.comment:
This element is a plain tile container. 
It's best used as an intermediate tile in a 2D grid. 
You can also add "is-ancestor", "is-parent", "is-child", and "is-vertical" classes to to make a custom Bulma-grid implementation.
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Grid.Tile msg) -> Bulma.Grid.Tile msg

values.name: tileAncestor
values.comment:
This should always be your outer-most tile.

    myGrid : Html msg
    myGrid
      = tileAncestor Auto []
        [ tileParent Auto [] 
          [ tileChild Auto [] []
          , tileChild Auto [] []
          ]
        [ tileParent Auto [] 
          [ tileChild Auto [] []
          , tileChild Auto [] []
          ]
        ]
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Grid.Tile msg) -> Html.Html msg

values.name: tileChild
values.comment: This tile holds your content! Its parent should always be `tileParent` or `verticalTileParent`.
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> Helpers.Htmls msg -> Bulma.Grid.Tile msg

values.name: tileParent
values.comment: Your tile-children must always be accompanied by a parent!
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Grid.Tile msg) -> Bulma.Grid.Tile msg

values.name: verticalTile
values.comment: If you want to stack tiles vertically, use a vertical tile!
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Grid.Tile msg) -> Bulma.Grid.Tile msg

values.name: verticalTileParent
values.comment: Your tile-children must always be accompanied by a parent!
values.type: Bulma.Grid.Width -> Helpers.Attrs msg -> List (Bulma.Grid.Tile msg) -> Bulma.Grid.Tile msg
